reviews.summary:
The paper addresses the problem of cultural misalignment in Large Language Models when simulating survey respondents from different regions. The authors propose OG-MAR (Ontology-Guided Multi-Agent Reasoning), a pipeline that:
1. Converts raw World Values Survey (WVS) respondent data into structured per-topic value summaries under a fixed taxonomy of 12 top-level domains and 76 fine-grained categories;
2. Constructs a cultural ontology of 150 natural-language object property pairs via Competency Questions, LLM-assisted generation across 6 regions, and expert consolidation;
3. At inference time, classifies an incoming question into relevant domains (via a fine-tuned DeBERTa-v2-xxlarge encoder), retrieves relevant ontology triples and demographically similar respondent profiles via dense embeddings (E5-base);
4. Instantiates K=5 value-persona agents, each conditioned on retrieved triples and one respondent's profile, then synthesizes their outputs via a Judgment Agent that enforces ontology consistency and demographic proximity.

Evaluation is conducted on 6 regional social-survey benchmarks (EVS, GSS, CGSS, ISD, LAPOP, Afrobarometer) across 4 LLM backbones (GPT-4o mini, Gemini 2.5 Flash Lite, Qwen 2.5, EXAONE 3.5). Tasks are cast as binary classification; accuracy and MAE are reported. Results show improvements over five baselines (Zero-shot, Role Assignment, Self-consistency, Debate, ValuesRAG) for most model/dataset combinations.
